@node "Nodes" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/Node"

 A 'Node' is one element in a @{"list" link Lists}.
 Especially in MoA it is eighter a module or a sublist.

@endnode
@node "Lists" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/Lists"

 A 'List' is a structure containing @{"nodes" Link Nodes}.
 Especially in MoA, a list can contain modules and lists itself.

 ( 'MoA' lists are trees for real )

@endnode

@node "DataFile" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/DataFile"

A Data-File is created by saving. It contains (in compressed form)
anything you ever stored with MoA.

Annotation: MoA-Info (see @{"Support" Link Support}) uses this data-file
            to display information on the module dalitracker is playing.

DataFiles are crunched using @{"XPK" Link XPK}.
@endnode

@node "DeliPlayers" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/DeliPlayers"

DeliPlayers are replay-modules used by @{"DeliTracker" Link DeliTracker}
for playing different music-formats.

MoA uses 'deliplayers' to identify formats not recognized by the
internal checkers.

Note: Moa does not support deliplayers that use the DTP_Process function.
      If Moa finds such a player it will not be used.
      DeliSID is such a player. Use the SID.checker instead for recognizing
      (Play/Deli)SID-modules.

@endnode

@node "DeliTracker" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/DeliTracker"

DeliTracker is the most powerfull moduleplayer for the Amiga.

DeliTracker is copyrighted by Peter Kunath and Frank Riffel
of Delirium Software.

DeliTracker is ShareWare.

@endnode

@node "ReqTools" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/ReqTools"

reqtools.library is a standard Amiga shared, runtime library. 
The purpose of ReqTools is to make it a lot quicker and easier to build
standard requesters into your programs.  ReqTools is designed with
Commodore's style guidelines in mind, all requesters have the
look-and-feel of AmigaDOS Release 2.

ReqTools is copyrighted by Nico François.

ReqTools is ShareWare.


@endnode

@node "XPK" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/XPK"

XPK is an interfacing standart between application programs and packer 
libraries. Every XPK application program can pack (and depack) data
with any XPK packer.

XPK is copyrighted, but freely distributable for non-commercial use. 
Some parts of XPK have a different legal status, ie. PD, GPL or
shareware.

Xpk was written by :

  Urban Dominik Mueller    umueller@amiga.physik.unizh.ch
  Bryan Ford               bryanf@hpmcaa.mcm.hp.com
  Peter Struijk            ddws0168@dutiws.tudelft.nl
  Christian von Roques     roques@karlsruhe.gmd.de
  Andre Beck               beck@freia.inf.tu-dresden.de
  Marc Zimmermann          zimmerma@ibr.cs.tu-bs.de
  Kristian Nielsen         bombadil@diku.dk
  Torsten Juergeleit       bj030@aix370.rrz.uni-koeln.de
  Matthias Scheler         tron@uni-paderborn.de
  Uwe Roehm                roehm@kirk.fmi.uni-passau.de
  Martin A. Blatter        blatter@amiga.physik.unizh.ch
  ...and more.

@endnode

@node "ASCIIList" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/ASCII Lists"

ASCII - lists are playin text files. 
@endnode

@node "Modules" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/Modules"

A typical amiga module consists of four parts :

1.:  instrument header, containing :
      [name]
      length
      volume
      [finetuning]
      repeatstart  --+-- for looped instruments
      repeatlength  /

2.: notedata header : containing length of the module, and maybe
                      replay order for the pattern data.

3.: notedata   : containing the notes to play

4.: intruments : eighter 8-Bit samples or intructions how to build a
                 synthetic instrument (sample).

Some modules are splitted in two parts (eg: TFMX), one containing
the headers and the notedata, the other the samples.

MIDI tunes don't look like this at all, they use predefined
instrument-tables.


For details read the documentation of your favorite Composing-Tool.

@endnode

@node "Features" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/Features"

(some features)	

- recognition of nearly any (amiga) music/sound format
  (anything @{"DeliTracker" link DeliTracker } recognizes
   and additionaly MIDI files)

- author recognition (ProTracker and clones)

- playtime calculation

- information display on modules of several formats
  (ProTracker, Kris, Laxity, Jamcracker, MIDI ...)

- flexible play function

- creates playlists for @{"DeliTracker" Link DeliTracker}

- ASCII list output

- external checkroutines (@{"DeliPlayers" Link DeliPlayers})

- handling of packed modules (@{"XPK" Link XPK})

- fast and flexible browse window

- fancy userinterface

@endnode

@node "PlaySID" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/PlaySID"

 PlaySID emulates the SID (sound) chip and the 6510/6502 CPU of the
 Commodore C64 computer.

 PlaySID is copyrighted by Hĺkan Sundell  and Ron Birk

 PlaySID is ShareWare.

 (see also '@{"Support" Link Support 41}')

@endnode


@node "Bugs" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/Bugs"

MoA has been tested a long time ... using Enforcer and Mungwall,
and should be free of hits.

Any known bugs have been removed but there might still be some
small and silly bugs left. If you think you found a bug please
@{"contact" link Address} me.

Thanks in advance.

@endnode

@node "Demo" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/Demo"

This is a incomplete version for public redistribution.
The following functions have been removed :

Moving     (same like '@{"Collect" Link Menu 124 }' but moves the files/modules
            to the directory of the target-list)
ListInfo   (displays the amount of modules and
            shortest, longest, average and total playtime of
            all modules in the list (recursive))
ReScan     (re-scans a module or all modules in a list)
Update     (scans all files in a directory which are NOT in
            the actual list)

You may use this demo-release up to 30 days, after this evalution
period you have to @{"register" link Registration }.


@endnode

@node "Support" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/Support"


There are (at this time) the following additional programs coming
with MoA. They will hopefuly help you.


MoA-Info         (MoA-Info.genie)
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

   This is a so called 'Genie' for DeliTracker 2 .
   Whenever you play a module with Delitracker 2 and MoA-Info
   is active it will search MoA's data-file for information on
   the active module.
   In case something was found, it is displayed in MoA-Info's window.
   This means whenever you play a module that is stored in MoA's
   datafile MoA-Info will display :

   name, author, copyright, releasedate, production, playtime
   and description.

   Simply add 'MoA-Info' as a Genie to Delitracker.
   The very first time you need to tell MoA-Info where you
   stored 'MoA's datafile. To do so press the 'config'
   button in DeliTracker's genie-window when MoA-Info is the
   active genie in the window. Now select MoA's datafile and
   acknowledge the filerequester.
   Last thing to do is saving 'MoA-Info's preferences
   so it will find the datafile anytime it is started.
   For this you need to open 'MoA-Info's window and
   select 'Save Prefs' in the 'Project' menu.    Done.

   If you don't know how to install a DeliTracker 2.0 genie
   please read DeliTracker's genie-docs.

   MoA needs not to be running to use MoA-Info.


----------------------------- --------------------------------------------


moa_PlaySID.checker is a external checker for MoA.
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
   It is a check-routine for @{"PlaySID" link PlaySID} modules which recognizes the
   Icon-related modules and the newer 'PSID' ID modules of PlaySID/DeliSID 2.x

   Basically 'PlaySID.checker' is a deliplayer but contains ONLY the
   check-code. Put it somewhere where MoA can find it but DeliTracker
   not.

   There is a SID-player for DeliTracker but as it uses the
   'DTP_Process' feature, MoA can not utilize it !
   

-------------------------------------------------------------------------


moa_ScreamTracker3.checker is a external checker for MoA
ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
   It is a check-routine for ScreamTracker 3 modules.
   Basically 'ScreamTracker3.checker' is a deliplayer but contains ONLY
   the check-code. Put it somewhere where MoA can find it but DeliTracker
   not.

   You will not need it if you have a 'ScreamTracker 3.0' deliplayer.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------

moa_8SVX.checker is a external checker for MoA.
moa_RIFF-WAVE.checker is a external checker for MoA.

   The IFF 8SCX and the RIFF WAVE deliplayers use the DTP_Process
   feature and can not be used for checking.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------


@endnode
@node "History" "Module Administrator 1.10 english documentation/History"

Version 1.10 (18th Sep 1994) (Oktoberfest release)
     - added    : rescan progress indicator
     - added    : comment parsing
     - replaced : gadtools-listview in browserwindow
                  (reduced memory usage, gained speed)
     - added    : variable text-offset in browser-list (bottom slider)
     - added    : variable length for string-items in the browser
                  and for printing/storing ASCII lists
     - fixed    : deliplayers using DTP_Process are no longer accepted
     - fixed    : the first non-executable file in the playersdirectory
                  stopped loading deliplayers
     - fixed    : when moving already existing files into a directory
                 'Skip' would replace it.
     - fixed    : playtime-calculation for Startrekker 4 modules
     - fixed    : rescanning of non-packed files trashed memory
     - enhanced : MIDI checker and MIDI info
     - added    : Tracker Packer 2 & 3 as internal checkers
     - replaced : 'actlist' string-gadget in the edit window
                   by a text-gadget.
     - preferences splitted into two windows
     - minor fixes
     - code-cleanup

Version 1.06 (26th Mai 1994)
     - saving datafiles now 3 times faster (using buffered IO)
     - fixed   : saving marked modules as ASCII list did loop forever

Version 1.05 (14th Mai 1994)
     - fixed   : deadlock when rescanning files with filesize < 5
     - fixed   : incorrect mark-rectange X-size in the edit window
     - fixed   : prefs 'Cancel'-gadget spelled incorrect
     - added   : super-change directory
     - fixed   : lists could be collected to themselves
     - rearranged the menu

Version 1.02 (01st Mai 1994)
     - removed : annoying requester in the demo version
     - added   : MIDI-checker and MIDI-info
     - fixed   : stack overflow while recursive scanning
     - fixed   : canceled delete operation did lock the editwindow
     - fixed   : bad and crypted XPK files had been added to the list
                  while scanning, even if 'recognized only' was set

Version 1.00
     (traded with the DeliTracker 2.01 update to registered users only)
     - initial release.

@endnode

